<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
<a class="spoiler" href="/questions/1732937-i-ve-been-wondering-why-do-you-guys-think">This question contains spoilers...</a>
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[I've been wondering. Why do you guys think Cherryh had Talley go on the ship with Mallory in the end? She did such a good job of showing his emotional turmoil when recalling Mallory's rape, but then she had him just go off with her at the end of the book. Why did she do that? An implication that by saving Downbelow Station at the end, all Mallory's past sins were forgiven? Because I really don't like the idea of that. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1732937'><a id="like_count_community_question_1732937" rel="nofollow" href="/rating/voters/1732937?resource_type=CommunityQuestion"><span class="likesCount">1 like</span></a>&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;<a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F57045.Downbelow_Station">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1732937-i-ve-been-wondering-why-do-you-guys-think">one year ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1732937-i-ve-been-wondering-why-do-you-guys-think">See all 3 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/7994057-william"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1330605151i/7994057._UX100_CR0,20,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/7994057-william">William</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<div class='spoiler'>
This answer contains spoilers…
<span class='spoilerAnswerText'>
<a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[
  
    Talley’s complicated. He’s running from want he cares about, because those people will unconsciously place expectations on him that he’s got no idea h<a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">…more</a>
    Talley’s complicated. He’s running from want he cares about, because those people will unconsciously place expectations on him that he’s got no idea how to respond to. When he was serving the Union, he was programmed to win people’s trust and then honour it only as far as required for Union objectives. That provided boundaries. Now he’s no longer an unquestioning Union drone, he has to figure out his own boundaries, and doesn’t want to inadvertently hurt those he cares about, or those they care about, while he does it. Hence he goes with Mallory.<br />I think it is unfair to characterise Mallory’s actions as rape in the early part of the book. There’s a marked power differential in their relationship, and we know Talley, between the Union programming and the partial Adjustment the doomed Russell station authorities subjected him to, isn’t really in a position to give consent, but Mallory doesn’t know that. It’s strongly inferred she doesn’t *want* to know anything about his past because she’s deliberately avoiding emotional entanglements. She’s a damaged person who’s deluded herself she’s just picked up another person with severe emotional baggage, who’s agreed to trade his body for safe passage away from Russell station. <br />So he’s choosing the devil he knows. They know what he is, and he knows what they are. He knows Mallory has an aversion to emotional intimacy. They aren’t going to be trying to push emotional intimacies onto him that he’s not sure how to respond to. It gives him the time to decide where his boundaries are. <br />There’s also the way that Pell’s newly-minted independence needs both Norway and the Merchanter Alliance. When a Merchant vessel is late, suspicion will inevitably fall on Norway. A Pell observer on board would count for a lot when Norway claims innocence. By the same token, a Pell observer on board would go far with insuring Norway doesn’t “accidentally” attack a vessel identifying itself as a member of the Merchanter Alliance. Talley can feel reasonably safe on board, because Norway puts at risk their docking rights at Pell if it returns without Talley in reasonable condition. <a href="#" rel="nofollow noopener">(less)</a>
  
 <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>
</span>
</div>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

<div class='flagAnswer'>
<a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link1180429" title="Flag this answer as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=1180429&amp;resource_type=CommunityAnswer&amp;return_url=%2Fquestions%2F1732937-i-ve-been-wondering-why-do-you-guys-think%2Fanswers%2F1180429-talley-s-complicated">flag</a>
</div>
