          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85062696-torin-kylara?shelf=space-opera">space-opera</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85062696-torin-kylara?shelf=2019-book-challenge">2019-book-challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/85062696-torin-kylara?shelf=hugo">hugo</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3094484046" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3090977962118457491">Oh this book is so good! With caveats, but let&apos;s get there in a minute.<br/><br/>So. I had reservations going into this book because it was written in the early 80s by a woman who was hiding the fact that she was a woman because of how sexist the field was at the time. So the fact that this book was so good and not horribly, caustically sexist was a huge, huge surprise! In a very good way! Now, a caveat to that is that 90% of the main character POVs in this book (of which there are many) are male. So auto</span>
  <span id="freeText3090977962118457491" style="display:none">Oh this book is so good! With caveats, but let's get there in a minute.<br /><br />So. I had reservations going into this book because it was written in the early 80s by a woman who was hiding the fact that she was a woman because of how sexist the field was at the time. So the fact that this book was so good and not horribly, caustically sexist was a huge, huge surprise! In a very good way! Now, a caveat to that is that 90% of the main character POVs in this book (of which there are many) are male. So automatically, ugh. However, the caveat to that is she was trying to pretend to be a man at this point! That's how sexist the field was at the time, remember? So of course most of the MCs are male. She was passing. And the female characters she did write are all strong women in their own rights. Not all likable, oh no, definitely not all likable, but not all the male characters are likable either, so there's a good parity in that at least.<br /><br />Anyway, the point is that despite all the trappings of a potentially sexist book, CJ Cherryh does an excellent job subverting that trope, and I greatly appreciate her effort in it. (Sidenote: Did you know her last name is actually Cherry, but publishers thought that sounded too "romance-y", so she changed it to Cherryh--with an h. Ha! Cause that's 1000% more sci-fi-y!)<br /><br />Now to the story itself. It was an absolutely fantastic thrill ride. Starts off strong <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[with a riot onboard a couple refugee ships and the danger of that riot spilling over onto the station <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>! Of course, this would be bad, since <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[riot on space station=really forking bad for the the space station <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>! And it just kicks off from there! The action is nonstop, and in the pauses of the action, Cherryh does some truly excellent character work. Talley and Damon and Elene are of course my favorite part of the book, and Cherryh does the hard work with their characterization. You really feel for all these characters and their lives and that only leads to you caring about the outcome of the book even more.<br /><br />There is one caveat to the characterization that I did not enjoy and it is one of the reasons the book got knocked down from a five star for me. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Why did Cherryh have Talley go on the ship with Mallory? She did such a good job of showing his emotional turmoil when recalling what Mallory did to him on the ship--presumably rape, although I don't recall if the book mentions it specifically--but then she had him just go off with her at the end of the book. Why did she do that? An implication that by saving Downbelow Station at the end, all Mallory's past sins were forgiven? Because I really don't like the idea of that. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I don't think I need to tell you any more to get you to read the book. If you're a fan of space operas with big stakes and big characterizations, you will jump at the bit to get to this one. Don't let the age fool you, this book is timeless (nearly! <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[remember the bit with the "tapes" everywhere?! and the pregnant woman drinking alcohol! ha! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, so don't hesitate to pick up a copy and give CJ Cherryh a try. I know I'll be looking for an excuse to read another book of hers, so have fun with your exploration, and I hope you enjoy!</span>
  <a data-text-id="3090977962118457491" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


